<font color="#FF0000">COMMENT FOR R. C. WEBB</font><br>
<tt>Tue Dec 17 22:19:43 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
History *is* a study of viewpoints. As I become older, I am more acutely aware of that. I can say that I am becomming a more informed historical &quot;consumer&quot; as time goes on.<br><br>
I feel that your pessimism about the process on these pages is undeserved. After all, we have the words and oral histories of soldiers and citizens in the American historical experience from the Revolutionary war and onwards. Diaries of Civil War Soldiers, letters from WW2 GI's, the diary of Anne Frank, are all examples of the rich historical legacy over which some opinionated stuffed shirts in academia have no control!<br><br>
The specific words written here may not reach into the future, but the points of view they express will in some manner. <br><br>
I feel people will care 100 years from now, just as we now revere the words passed on to us from our past.<br><br>
I am a Vietnam Verteran. I feel now more connected with that which is part of our legacy more than ever. I do not feel that my opinions must be transcendant. I feel that I must become part of the very diverse whole. 
<p><code>-- art16@ix.netcom.com  (Arthur Varanelli) </code><p>


